    \"tweet_text\": \"Humans communicate through language and interact with the world through vision, yet most multimodal models are language-first. What happens when we go beyond language? 🤔\\nBeyond Language Modeling: a deep dive into the design space of truly native multimodal models\\n\\nPaper: https://t.co/KOpmL1PItn\\nProject:\"
  },
  {
    \"status_url\": \"https://x.com/backproplabsai/status/2029483871591710862\",
    \"tweet_text\": \"𝗕𝗲𝘆𝗼𝗻𝗱 𝗟𝗮𝗻𝗴𝘂𝗮𝗴𝗲 𝗠𝗼𝗱𝗲𝗹𝗶𝗻𝗴: 𝗔𝗻 𝗘𝘅𝗽𝗹𝗼𝗿𝗮𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝗼𝗳 𝗠𝘂𝗹𝘁𝗶𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗮𝗹 𝗣𝗿𝗲𝘁𝗿𝗮𝗶𝗻𝗶𝗻𝗴 reveals why the field still lacks a clear map of how to build truly unified models that see and speak. While language‑only pretraining has saturated, researchers have little guidance on which visual encodings, data mixes, or architectures actually work when language and vision are learned together from scratch.\\n\\nThe authors tackled this blind spot by training a single autoregressive model from the ground up with the Transfusion framework—next‑token prediction for text and diffusion‑based next‑visual‑state prediction for images and video. They kept compute constant across experiments and varied (i) visual encoders (VAEs, semantic models, raw pixels), (ii) data sources (pure text, raw video, image‑text pairs, action‑conditioned video), (iii) architectural choices (modality‑specific FFNs vs. Mixture‑of‑Experts), and (iv) scaling regimes (IsoFLOP analyses) to isolate what truly drives multimodal learning.\\n\\n- 𝗥𝗲𝗽𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗲𝗻𝘁𝗮𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝗔𝘂𝘁𝗼𝗲𝗻𝗰𝗼𝗱𝗲𝗿𝘀 (𝗥𝗔𝗘) 𝗲𝗺𝗲𝗿𝗴𝗲 𝗮𝘀 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝗼𝗽𝘁𝗶𝗺𝗮𝗹 𝘃𝗶𝘀𝘂𝗮𝗹 𝗯𝗮𝗰𝗸𝗯𝗼𝗻𝗲, delivering top‑tier performance on both generation (low diffusion loss, high FID) and understanding (VQA accuracy) with a single encoder.  \\n- 𝗩𝗶𝘀𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗹𝗮𝗻𝗴𝘂𝗮𝗴𝗲 𝗱𝗮𝘁𝗮 𝗮𝗿𝗲 𝗰𝗼𝗺𝗽𝗹𝗲𝗺𝗲𝗻𝘁𝗮𝗿𝘆, not competitive; mixing text with video or image‑text pairs preserves language perplexity while unlocking visual capabilities.  \\n- 𝗪𝗼𝗿𝗹𝗱‑𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗲𝗹𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗮𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝗶𝗲𝘀 𝘀𝘂𝗿𝗳𝗮𝗰𝗲 𝗮𝘂𝘁𝗼𝗺𝗮𝘁𝗶𝗰𝗮𝗹𝗹𝘆, as models trained on diverse video and action‑conditioned data learn to predict future visual states from textual actions without task‑specific tuning.  \\n- 𝗠𝗶𝘅𝘁𝘂𝗿𝗲‑𝗼𝗳-𝗘𝘅𝗽𝗲𝗿𝘁𝘀 (𝗠𝗼𝗘) 𝘀𝗰𝗮𝗹𝗲𝘀 𝗲𝗳𝗳𝗶𝗰𝗶𝗲𝗻𝘁𝗹𝘆, providing the massive capacity needed for language while allocating extra resources to the data‑hungry vision stream, naturally forming modality‑specific expert groups.  \\n- 𝗦𝗰𝗮𝗹𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗹𝗮𝘄𝘀 𝗲𝘅𝗽𝗼𝘀𝗲 𝗮 𝘃𝗶𝘀𝗶𝗼𝗻‑𝗹𝗮𝗻𝗴𝘂𝗮𝗴𝗲 𝗮𝘀𝘆𝗺𝗺𝗲𝘁𝗿𝘆—vision requires far more data than language—but MoE architectures bridge this gap, enabling balanced growth of multimodal competence.\\n\\nBy demystifying the design space and showing how a single, scalable architecture can harmonize the divergent data demands of sight and speech, this work charts a practical path toward foundation models that truly understand and generate across modalities, opening doors for richer AI assistants, more robust perception‑action systems, and cross‑modal research breakthroughs.  \\n\\n#MultimodalAI #FoundationModels #AIResearch\"
