[
  {
    "status_url": "https://x.com/XiaoyangWu_/status/2029262234988523749",
    "tweet_text": "Introducing Utonia ✨\n\nA question we have wanted to ask for years:\nCan one encoder emerge from all point clouds, and then benefit all point clouds?\n\nIndoor scans 🏠, outdoor LiDAR 🚗, object CAD 📦, remote sensing 🛰️, even video-lifted 3D🎥 - instead of treating them as separate worlds, Utonia trains a unified Point Transformer V3 across all of them.\n\nThe goal is simple, but the implication is not:\nOne representation, across heterogeneous 3D domains.\n\nWhat makes it work is surprisingly simple:\n🔹Canonical observing granularity across point clouds\n🔹Causal masking of color/normal cues for modality robustness\n🔹RoPE for handling orientation priors without collapsing to one domain\nThe most interesting part is that joint training is not merely “one model for many datasets.”\nIt produces emergent cross-domain behaviors: better transfer, stronger geometric abstraction, graceful handling of occlusion, and even part-level semantics without explicit supervision.\n\n🚀 Paper: https://t.co/bajIvVvxXJ\n💻 Code: https://t.co/CDLcbabRNT\n🤗 Demo: https://t.co/4BAhHBGXzE\n\nThanks to our co-authors: @Yujia_Zhang_, Yunhan Yang, Xianzhe Fan, Han Li, Yuechen Zhang, Zehao Huang, Naiyan Wang, @HengshuangZhao"
  },
  {
    "status_url": "https://x.com/backproplabsai/status/2029454115483611598",
    "tweet_text": "𝗨𝘁𝗼𝗻𝗶𝗮: 𝗧𝗼𝘄𝗮𝗿𝗱 𝗢𝗻𝗲 𝗘𝗻𝗰𝗼𝗱𝗲𝗿 𝗳𝗼𝗿 𝗔𝗹𝗹 𝗣𝗼𝗶𝗻𝘁 𝗖𝗹𝗼𝘂𝗱𝘀 envisions a single self‑supervised transformer that can ingest sparse 3D data from remote‑sensing LiDAR, indoor RGB‑D scans, CAD models, and video‑derived point clouds—domains that traditionally require bespoke pipelines. \n\nThe obstacle is that point clouds differ wildly in density, sampling pattern, and auxiliary channels (color, normals). Prior SSL methods either ignore these mismatches or hard‑code domain‑specific tricks, causing representations to cluster by dataset rather than by geometry, and limiting transfer across tasks. \n\nTo bridge the gap, the authors train a unified Point‑Transformer V3 on 250 k cross‑domain clouds plus 1 M CAD assets, introducing three domain‑agnostic fixes: \n\n- 𝗖𝗮𝘂𝘀𝗮𝗹 𝗠𝗼𝗱𝗮𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗕𝗹𝗶𝗻𝗱𝗶𝗻𝗴 – random masking of optional channels (color, normals) at both sample and point levels, forcing the encoder to rely on geometry while still exploiting available cues. \n- 𝗣𝗲𝗿𝗰𝗲𝗽𝘁𝘂𝗮𝗹 𝗚𝗿𝗮𝗻𝘂𝗹𝗮𝗿𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗰𝗮𝗹𝗲 – dynamic rescaling of coordinates to a shared “angular” granularity, preserving upright bias for scene‑scale scans while encouraging rotation invariance for object‑scale data. \n- 𝗥𝗼𝗣𝗘 𝗣𝗼𝘀𝗶𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻𝗮𝗹 𝗘𝗻𝗰𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗻𝗴 – applying rotary embeddings directly to attention queries/keys, giving a continuous, density‑robust positional signal that aligns across disparate sampling patterns. \n\nKey empirical findings (linear probing, decoder probing, and full fine‑tuning) include: \n\n- State‑of‑the‑art indoor semantic segmentation: 81.1 % mIoU on ScanNet and 78.1 % on S3DIS, surpassing prior universal models. \n- Competitive outdoor performance: comparable mIoU to specialized LiDAR encoders on SemanticKITTI while using a single model. \n- Object‑centric tasks benefit as well, closing the gap with domain‑specific backbones on ModelNet40 classification after fine‑tuning. \n- Emergent behaviors such as gravity‑aligned scene features coexisting with rotation‑invariant object features, and improved spatial reasoning when Utonia embeddings are fed into vision‑language models. \n\nThese results show that, once the core mismatches are neutralized, a single point‑cloud encoder can learn a geometry‑centric representation that transfers across scales, sensors, and modalities. This paves the way for foundation models in sparse 3D perception, unlocking more robust AR/VR experiences, autonomous‑driving perception stacks, and robot manipulation policies that can reason about space with a shared visual language. \n\n#3DVision #SelfSupervisedLearning #Robotics"
